snippet.textDisplay: Hypocrite. Im sorry, but its the truth. We wanted every single manager post fergie out because of style of play. Now we have ole, he sold us a dream in style of play, got the job and went back to being defensive. And now we are going to be told to back the manager when ole is playing a style of play that is exactly what us fans have been moaning about for years. My standards wont be lowered, and that is why I want ole out and poch in.  Ole can go and prove himself with a lower team and lets see how that goes. He is learning on the job, we can see, the players keep saying he is learning everyday, we are man united. Not some league 2 club giving a shot to a manager like Sol Campbell and hoping for the best. There are levels to all this and for me, its as simple as, I dont like ole's style of play. Formation, tactics, in game management like subs,  Zonal Marking, everytime he opens his mouth in interviews he gets caught out with something. The signs are there.

snippet.textDisplay:
I think the boys gave their all and we can't fault anyone of them. Wan-bissaka seems like a bargain at the price we got him. Fred has grown in leaps and bounds. Ighalo's abilities as a striker is fantastic. Martial is just a goal shy of equalling his best season when he signed newly. With Jones, Pereira, lingard, smalling, Sanchez, pogba, rojo likely to leave, we can raise ample cash to get players that will bring the same positivity that Bruno has brought and not the ones concerned about their hairstyles or clothing line
When the transfer season starts, our first business must be getting rid of Jones.

snippet.textDisplay:
-3 at the back suits this team very well
-Competition for places
-A lot of good habits being displayed
-Fast, exciting, energetic performances
-Bruno has added that quality, arrogance and confidence that the team was desperate for
-Injuries calming down at just the right time of the season


This squad can challenge for 4th and have a good cup run, tight at the back and still finding ways to score goals. Chelsea and Leicester need to be looking over their shoulder. United's biggest challenge will be getting points from teams that sit deep but the rest of the top 8 won't keep up. Ole is no genius but the progress is plain to see.
